[[File:0150 Altes Museum Empress Faustina the Elder anagoria.JPG|thumb|Bust of Faustina Major in the Altes Museum (Berlin)]]
'''Annia Galeria Faustina''', sometimes referred to as '''Faustina I''' ([[Latin]]: '''Faustina Major''';<ref>An inscription from Liguria ({{CIL|05|07617}}) refers to her (in the genitive) as <small>DIVAE FAVSTINAE MAIORIS</small>.</ref> born on February 16<ref>{{harvp|Levick|2014|page=137}}, citing the ''[[Feriale Duranum]]'' 3.7.</ref><ref>''Inscriptiones Italiae'' [http://db.edcs.eu/epigr/epi_einzel_en.php?p_belegstelle=InscrIt-13-02,+00043 '''13'''(02): 43].</ref> around 100 CE;<ref>{{harvp|Levick|2014|page=169}}, estimates Faustina the Elder's birth year as {{circa|97}} CE, while noting the estimate of {{circa|105}} in {{cite book|author=D. Kienast |title=Römische Kaisertabelle: Grunzüge einer römischen Kaiserchronologie |location=Darmstadt |publisher=Wissenschaflische Gesellschaft |date=1990}}.</ref> died in October or November of 140 CE<ref>Birley, Anthony. ''Marcus Aurelius'', Routledge, p. 243. Routledge, 2000. {{ISBN|0-415-17125-3}}</ref><ref>According to S. Vidman's interpretation of the ''Fasti Ostienses'' (1982, p. 122; cited by {{harvp|Beckmann|2012|page=22}}), Faustina died sometime in the range 21-23 October, while her funeral occurred sometime between 6 and 12 November. See Beckmann (2012), p. 22.</ref>), was a Roman empress and wife of the [[Roman emperor]] [[Antoninus Pius]]. The emperor [[Marcus Aurelius]] was her nephew and later became her adopted son, along with Emperor [[Lucius Verus]].  She died early in the principate of Antoninus Pius, but continued to be prominently commemorated as a ''[[Glossary_of_ancient_Roman_religion#divus|diva]]'', posthumously playing a prominent symbolic role during his reign.<ref name="pietas"/>

==Early life==
Faustina was the only known daughter of [[Roman consul|consul]] and prefect [[Marcus Annius Verus]] and [[Rupilia|Rupilia Faustina]].<ref name="livius">{{cite web |url=http://www.livius.org/fa-fn/faustina/faustina_i.html |title=Faustina I |website=Livius.org |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> Her brothers were consul [[Marcus Annius Libo]] and [[praetor]] [[Marcus Annius Verus (praetor)|Marcus Annius Verus]]. Her maternal aunts were Roman Empress [[Vibia Sabina]] and [[Matidia Minor]]. Her paternal grandfather was named Marcus Annius Verus, like her father, while her maternal grandparents were [[Salonia Matidia]] (niece of Roman Emperor [[Trajan]]) and suffect consul [[Libo Rupilius Frugi|Lucius Scribonius Libo Rupilius Frugi Bonus]]. Faustina was born and raised in [[Rome]].

While a private citizen, she married Antoninus Pius between 110 and 115 CE. Faustina bore Antoninus four children: two sons and two daughters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lawrence.edu/dept/art/buerger/catalogue/098.html |title=Draped bust of Faustina the Elder (aureus of Antoninus Pius) |website=Bearers of Meaning: The Ottilia Buerger Collection of Ancient and Byzantine Coins at Lawrence University |author=K.L.M. |date=1996 |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref> These were:
* Marcus Aurelius Fulvius Antoninus (died before 138); his sepulchral inscription has been found at the [[Mausoleum of Hadrian]] in Rome.<ref name="livius"/><ref name="forvm">{{cite web|url=http://www.forumancientcoins.com/numiswiki/view.asp?key=Faustina%20Senior |title=Faustina Senior |website=FORVM ANCIENT COINS |accessdate=2015-09-21}}</ref>
* Marcus Galerius Aurelius Antoninus (died before 138); his sepulchral inscription has been found at the Mausoleum of Hadrian in Rome.<ref name="livius"/><ref name="forvm"/> He is commemorated by a high-quality series of bronze coins, possibly struck at Rome, though their language is Greek.<ref>{{harvp|Beckmann|2012|page=83}}. His name appears as <small>ΓΑΛΕΡΙΟϹ ΑΝΤⲰΝΙΝΟϹ</small> (''Galerios Antôninos'') on these coins.</ref>
* Aurelia Fadilla (died in 135); she married Aelius Lamia Silvanus or Syllanus. She appears to have had no children with her husband and her sepulchral inscription has been found in [[Italy]].<ref name="livius"/><ref name="forvm"/>
* Annia Galeria Faustina Minor or [[Faustina the Younger]] (between 125-130 to 175), a future Roman Empress; she married her maternal cousin, future Roman Emperor [[Marcus Aurelius]]. She was the only child who survived to see Antoninus and Faustina elevated to the imperial rank.<ref name="livius"/><ref name="forvm"/>

According to the unreliable ''[[Augustan History|Historia Augusta]]'', there were rumours while Antoninus was proconsul of [[Asia (Roman province)|Asia]] that Faustina conducted herself with "excessive frankness and levity".<ref>''[[Augustan History|Historia Augusta]]: Antoninus Pius'' [http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Roman/Texts/Historia_Augusta/Antoninus_Pius*.html 3.7] (the original phrase is ''nimiam libertatem et uiuendi facilitatem''). {{harvp|Levick|2014|pages=79-80}}, analyzes this passage with some scepticism. The ''[[Augustan History|Historia Augusta]]''’s reliability as a historical source is considered to be patchy (see the caveats in, for example ''The Cambridge History of Classical Literature: Volume 2, Latin Literature, Part 5, The Later Principate'', E. J. Kenney, Wendell Vernon Clausen, pp.&nbsp;43, 45, [[Cambridge University Press]], 1983, {{ISBN|0521273714}}; or at {{cite web|url=http://www.livius.org/hi-hn/ha/hist_aug.html |title=Historia Augusta |accessdate=2015-09-21 |author=Jona Lendering}}).</ref>

==Empress==
[[File:Buste de Faustine l'Ancienne 3a.jpg|left|thumb|Bust of Faustina in the Musei Capitolini (side view; note the distinctive hairstyle)]]

On July 10, 138, her uncle, the emperor [[Hadrian]], died and her husband became the new emperor, as Antoninus was Hadrian's adopted son and heir. Faustina became Roman Empress and the Senate accorded her the title of ''[[Augusta (honorific)|Augusta]]''.<ref name="livius"/>  As empress, Faustina was well respected and was renowned for her beauty and wisdom.  Throughout her life, as a private citizen and as empress, Faustina was involved in assisting charities for the poor and sponsoring and assisting in the education of Roman children, particularly girls.{{citation needed|date=November 2015}} A letter between [[Marcus Cornelius Fronto|Fronto]] and [[Antoninus Pius]] has sometimes been taken as an index of the latter's devotion to her.<ref>Antoninus Pius declares that he would rather live in exile on the island of [[Gyaros]] with Faustina than on the Palatine Hill without her. Fronto ''ad Antoninum Pium'' 2.2. However, the "dear Faustina" referred to may instead have been [[Faustina the Younger|Pius' daughter]]. {{harvp|Levick|2014|pages=60-61}}.</ref>

After Antoninus Pius' accession to the principate, the couple never left Italy; instead, they divided their time between Rome, Antoninus' favourite estate at [[Lorium]], and other properties at [[Lanuvium]], [[Tusculum]], and [[Segni|Signia]].{{sfnp|Levick|2014|page=57}}

Faustina's personal style was evidently much admired and emulated. Her distinctive hairstyle, consisting of braids pulled back in a bun behind or on top of her head, was imitated for two or three generations in the Roman world.{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|pages=10, 16}}

Several provincial groups chose to honour her while she was empress: a company of couriers in [[Ephesus]] named themselves after her,{{sfnp|Levick|2014|page=122}} while a company of [[Clapper (musical instrument)|clapper]]-players in Puteoli dedicated an altar to her in her own lifetime.<ref>{{harvp|Levick|2014|page=122}}. The inscription in question is {{CIL|10|1643}}.</ref>

== Death and legacy ==
[[File:Statue of Faustina the Elder, wife of Antoninus Pius, from the Nymphaeum of Herodes Atticus at Olympia, dating from between 149 and 153 AD (posthumous), Olympia Archaeological Museum, Greece (14003833782).jpg|thumb|right|Statue of Faustina the Elder at [[Herodes Atticus]]' nymphaeum at Olympia.]]

Faustina died near Rome in 140, perhaps at Antoninus Pius' estate at [[Lorium]].{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=22}} Antoninus was devastated at Faustina's death and took several steps to honor her memory. He had the Senate [[Imperial cult (Rome)|deify her]] (her ''[[apotheosis]]'' was portrayed on an [[column of Antoninus Pius|honorary column]]) and dedicate the [[Temple of Antoninus and Faustina|Temple of Faustina]] to her in the [[Roman Forum]].<ref name="livius"/> The Senate authorized gold and silver statues of her, including an image to appear in the [[Circus (building)|circus]],<ref>''[[Augustan History|HA]]'' Pius 6.7.</ref> where it might be displayed in a ''carpentum'' (a kind of covered waggon) or ''currus elephantorum'' (a cart drawn by elephants).{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|pages=32-33}} Antoninus also ordered various coins with her portrait struck, inscribed <small>DIVA FAVSTINA</small> ("Divine Faustina") and elaborately decorated. He also established a charity called ''Puellae Faustinianae'' ("Girls of Faustina") to assist orphaned Roman girls and created a new ''alimenta'' (see [[Grain supply to the city of Rome]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-emperors.org/tonypis.htm |title=Antoninus Pius |website=De Imperatoribus Romanis: An Online Encyclopedia of Roman Emperors |author=Richard D. Weigel |accessdate=2015-09-21 }}</ref> Her remains were interred in the [[Mausoleum of Hadrian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/~grout/encyclopaedia_romana/romanurbs/mausoleum.html |title=Mausoleum of Hadrian |accessdate=2015-11-12 |date=n.d. |author=James Grout |website=Encyclopædia Romana}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=[[Realencyclopädie der Classischen Altertumswissenschaft]] |chapter-url=https://de.wikisource.org/wiki/RE:Annius_120 |chapter=Annius 120  |date=1894 |author=Paul von Rohden}}</ref> Certain cities struck coin issues in honour of the "divine Faustina" ({{lang-grc|<small>[[:wikt:θεά#Ancient Greek|ΘΕΑ]] ΦΑΥϹΤΕΙΝΑ</small>}});<ref>{{cite web |url=http://rpc.ashmus.ox.ac.uk/imperial/faustina-i/ |title=Faustina I (138–141, and later deification coins) |website=Roman Provincial Coinage Online |accessdate=2015-09-21 |date=2015 }}</ref> the most notable such cities were [[Delphi]], [[Alexandria]], [[Bosra|Bostra]], and [[Nicopolis]].<ref>{{harvp|Beckmann|2012|p=75}}. The spelling ΦΑΥΣΤΙΝΑ was used in Alexandria, ΦΑΥΣΤΕΙΝΑ elsewhere in the [[Praetorian prefecture of the East|East]]; both spellings could be found in Delphi.</ref> Martin Beckmann suggests that the coins of Nicopolis might have been minted at Rome and given out as imperial largesse at the [[Actia|Actian Games]].{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=81}} The coins issued in the wake of Faustina's funeral illustrate her elaborate funeral pyre, which may have influenced the design of later private mausolea;{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|pages=23-27}} the deities [[Pietas]] and [[Aeternitas]], among others;<ref>Beckmann (2012) considers that Pietas and Aeternitas are evocative of "the 'spiritual side' of Faustina's divinisation" (p. 19).</ref> and an eagle (or less often a winged genius) bearing a figure aloft, with the legend <small>CONSECRATIO</small> (i.e. Faustina's ascension into heaven).{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|pages=23, 28-30}} Coins of Faustina were sometimes incorporated into jewellery and worn as amulets.{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|pages=17-18}}

[[File:DIVA FAUSTINA-RIC III 343 (Pius)-2600477.jpg|left|upright=1.33|thumb|A denarius struck in honour of Faustina Major, depicting [[Temple of Antoninus and Faustina|her temple]] with the abbreviated legend <small>AED&thinsp;DIV&thinsp;FAVSTINAE</small> (‘temple of the divine Faustina’)]]
[[File:Base de la columna Antonina 01 crop.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.33|Depiction of Pius and Faustina being borne aloft on the back of a winged figure. From the base of the [[Column of Antoninus Pius]].]]

The posthumous cult of Faustina was exceptionally widespread, and Faustina's image continued to be omnipresent throughout Antoninus Pius' principate.{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|page=6}} A colossal marble head, believed to be that of Faustina and discovered in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|website=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/sci/tech/7560833.stm |title=Head of Roman empress unearthed |date=2008-08-14 |accessdate=2015-09-24}}</ref> figured as one of several monumental imperial statues at the ancient site of [[Sagalassos]] in today's [[Turkey]]. In Olympia, [[Herodes Atticus]] dedicated a nymphaeum that displayed statues of Faustina and other Antonines as well as his own ancestors.{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|page=11}} Faustina also appears on the [[:commons:Category:Parthian Monument|Parthian Monument]] at Ephesus commemorating members of the imperial family.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=91}} Bergmann and Watson have characterized the commemoration of Faustina as central to Antoninus Pius' political persona.<ref name="pietas">{{harvp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|page=6}}: “Antoninus’s ideological program was based upon his ''pietas'' (loyalty to family, state, and the gods) and the most concerted expression of Antoninus’s piety was Faustina’s consecration.”</ref>{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|page=11}} One larger-than-life statue, discovered ''in situ'' near the Termini railway station at Rome, appears to depict Faustina as [[Concordia (goddess)|Concordia]], with a [[patera]] and cornucopia; it would have been displayed alongside statues of [[Diana (goddess)|Diana Lucifera]] and [[Apollo]]-[[Sol (god)|Sol]] in [[Thermae|baths]] privately owned but available to the public.<ref>{{harvp|Beckmann|2012|pages=85-86}}. The statue is [http://capitolini.info/scu00048/?lang=en now on display] in the Musei Capitolini.</ref>

Antoninus and Faustina were officially held up as such exemplars of conjugal harmony that newlyweds were directed to pray at an altar of Antoninus and Faustina that they might live up to their example.{{sfnp|Freisenbruch|2010|page=209}} This was evidently the case in Ostia,<ref>Thus {{harvp|Beckmann|2012|pages=36-37}}, arguing from the evidence of an inscription from Ostia ({{CIL|14|5326}}).</ref> and probably so in Rome.<ref>{{harvp|Beckmann|2012|page=37}}, suggests that [[Cassius Dio]] (''Roman History'' 72.31.1) may have been mistaken in stating that such a practice in Rome at the temple precinct of Venus and Dea Roma concerned an altar of [[Marcus Aurelius]] and [[Faustina the Younger]] rather than one of Antoninus Pius and Faustina the Elder.</ref>

The [[Temple of Antoninus and Faustina|Temple of Faustina]] is thought to have been dedicated in 144 CE.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=19}} It is a grand{{sfnp|Levick|2014|pages=123-124}} [[Portico#Roman hexastyle|hexastyle]] structure{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=44}} with [[Corinthian order|Corinthian columns]],{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=46}} possibly designed originally to be a temple of [[Ceres (goddess)|Ceres]].{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=48}} Depictions on coins appear to show a cult image of Faustina seated on a throne and holding a tall staff in her left hand.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=67}} Faustina's portrait on coins from this period is often crowned as well as veiled, which may also recall a feature of Faustina's cult image from the temple.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=50}} 

[[File:Piranesi-16063.jpg|right|thumb|upright=1.1|The church of [[Sant'Urbano alla Caffarella, Rome|Sant'Urbano alla Caffarella]] near Rome, originally built as a private shrine of Ceres and Faustina]]
The deified Faustina was associated particularly closely with [[Ceres (goddess)|Ceres]], who featured prominently on coins of Faustina; for some years, the torch-bearing Ceres was the dominant motif in her gold coinage.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=62}} Herodes Atticus venerated Faustina as the “new [[Demeter]]” (the Greek equivalent of Ceres) at a private sanctuary he established outside Rome,{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|page=14}} now the church of [[Sant'Urbano alla Caffarella, Rome|Sant'Urbano]].{{sfnp|Levick|2014|page=127}} In addition to Ceres, [[Vesta (deity)|Vesta]] and [[Juno (deity)|Juno]] feature prominently in Faustina's coinage.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|page=71}} She was also associated with the [[Cybele|Magna Mater]] and at Cyrene with [[Isis]]; at [[Sardis]] she was worshipped conjointly with [[Artemis]].{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|page=14}} 

Ten years after Faustina's death, a new commemorative coinage was introduced, featuring the legend [[Aeternitas]] ('eternity'); such coins may have been introduced to be distributed at a public ceremony in her memory.{{sfnp|Beckmann|2012|pages=63-64}}

After Antoninus Pius' death, his adoptive sons and successors [[Marcus Aurelius]] and [[Lucius Verus]] erected the [[Column of Antoninus Pius]], which dramatically depicted Antoninus and Faustina being elevated heavenward together on the back of a winged figure.{{sfnp|Freisenbruch|2010|page=210}}

Faustina continued to be commemorated in certain Renaissance depictions as a “model wife”.{{sfnp|Bergmann|Watson|1999|pages=12-13}}

